The first virtual provider is already coming to Czechia this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for a long time.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers work at the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on mobile.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming fees, there is as likely a paradoxic situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fighting year.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile radio providers like to shrink that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classical provider with its own network no longer has a great deal of opportunities (usually he would hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile phone market brought a significant reduction in the price, which then also had to respond to the classic mobile operators.
There were similar votes in the United Kingdom before the entry of such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile.
However, it has shown that there is space for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not need to look for examples for a long time.
In February this we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus climb to the country's five largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:phone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual provider is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
To be able to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, but often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half more cheap than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a very good draw to put on a non-slice target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider who likes them and can trust them," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
