The psychology of the overboy - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus to over-evaluate the celebrations.
Neurologists and economic researchers of the University of New York have now been able to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves in a competition, such as a auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play lotto while the other participated in a gambling action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were investigated by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain ring, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent’s overboying plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that price increase was explained by avoiding an overreaction of the Striatum.
In order to undermine their thesis, the economists in the research group have further investigated the follow-up of the money.
In this case, three groups should offer to a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, and then they made their interventions.
In addition, another group was promised $15 reward, in the case that they come out of the game as a winner.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which were also lost in the case of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that the emphasis on the one was on the win, while the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologians, however, the members of the group playing "contrary to losing" were ready for higher inputs than those in the control or "winn" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have only founded the practices observed in auctions so far with the joy of gaining, or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories was dissolved thanks to the illustrative neurological process, so that we now have a third explanation parat" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the economic faculty of the University of New York.
